• Introduction to Host Discovery

Host Discovery is the process of identifying live (active) hosts/devices on a
network before performing further enumeration such as port scanning, service
detection, or vulnerability assessment.

A host can be:
• Desktop computer
• Laptop
• Server
• Router
• Switch (management interface)
• Printer
• IoT device
• Mobile phone

Why Host Discovery is Important?

Before scanning ports, you must know:
• Which systems are online?
• Which IP addresses are in use?
• Which hosts respond to network requests? 

• Types of Host Discovery Techniques

Technique                   |  Protocol Used
------------------------------------------------
ICMP Ping Sweep             |       ICMP
ARP Scan                    |       ARP
TCP Ping                    |       TCP
UDP Ping                    |       UDP
NetBIOS Discovery           |     NetBIOS
DNS Discovery               |       DNS
------------------------------------------------

• ICMP Ping Sweep

ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol) is commonly used to determine
whether a host is reachable.

How It Works
Scanner → ICMP Echo Request
Target → ICMP Echo Reply
If Echo Reply is received: Host is Alive

• ARP Discovery

ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) maps IP addresses to MAC addresses.

How It Works
Who has 192.168.1.10?
Tell 192.168.1.100
Target replies:
192.168.1.10 is at
00:11:22:33:44:55

• TCP Ping Discovery

Some hosts block ICMP requests.
Instead, send a TCP packet to a common port.

Example
TCP SYN → Port 80
If a response is received:
Host is likely active

• UDP Ping Discovery

UDP packets are sent to a target port.

Common target:
53 DNS
161 SNMP
Response
If an ICMP Port Unreachable message is returned:
Host is alive

• NetBIOS Discovery (Windows Networks)

Windows systems often use NetBIOS for file and printer sharing.
Common Port - 137 UDP

• DNS-Based Discovery

DNS can reveal active systems.

Example Records
server.company.com
mail.company.com
vpn.company.com

